rial infrastructure of capitalism. Each chapter looks to what literally appears in the backgrounds of videos and images: the houses, cars, warehouses, and spaces of the market that point back to the manufacturing and circulation of consumer goods. Demonstrating the material reality of producing the self as a commodity, The Influencer Factory makes a crucial contribution to our understanding of contemporary economic life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCapitalismxSocial aspects2DLC. 0aCapitalismxSocial aspects. 0aCorporationsxSocial aspects2DLC. 0aCorporationsxSocial aspects. 0aInternet personalities2DLC. 0aInternet personalities. 0aSelfxEconomic aspects2DLC. 0aSelfxEconomic aspects. 0aSelfxSocial aspects2DLC. 0aSelfxSocial aspects. 0aSocial mediaxEconomic aspects2DLC. 0aSocial mediaxEconomic aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aCapitalism.  aCorporate Personhood.  aCultural Production.  aInfrastructure.  aInternet.  aLabor.  aMarxism.  aSocial Media.  aVisual Culture.  aYouTube.1 aGuinness, Katherine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363880840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503638808423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503638808/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles